vectorData.altText:
Papillary layer 
Consists of loose CT, rich in collagen type I, delicate collagen type III (reticular fibres) and fine elastic fibres. It is richly vascularized for nourishment of the overlying epidermis. Numerous cell types can be found in this layer.
Reticular layer 
This layer is thicker and less cellular than the papillary layer.
It consists of dense irregular CT dominated by:
coarser bundles of collagen type I which provides tensile strength
elastic fibres     , which impart resiliency, or the ability to stretch and bounce back
Fibre bundles aligned along regular tension lines in the skin, “Langer’s lines”     .
fibres may break with rapid stretch and not recoil, thus causing “stretch marks”
skin incisions made parallel to Langer’s lines heal with the least scarring
That's right! The reticular layer of dermis is made up of dense irregular CT with coarse bundles of collage type I fibres and elastic fibres.
